places.description:
The Ponte 25 de Abril suspension bridge is one of Lisbon’s most notable landmarks as it spans the River Tagus at the narrowest point. The date name remembers the Portuguese Carnation Revolution of 25 April 1974. Crossing the Ponte 25 de Abril bridge makes for a fantastic entrance to Lisbon.

Source: Lisbon Portugal Guide

places.place_address: R. Academia das Ciências 19, 1249 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
The Academy of Sciences of Lisbon was created in 1779 as an institution to promote the advancement of science and learning for the progress and prosperity of the country.

Source: European Comission

places.place_address: R. Dom Pedro V 129, 1250-096 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
On an unassuming corner of the Príncipe Real neighbourhood sits A Cevicheria, a restaurant dedicated to south-american cuisine, especially Peruvian tapas and Ceviche, headed by Portuguese Chef Kiko Martins.

Source: Four Seasons

The Águas Livres Aqueduct is a historic aqueduct in the city of Lisbon, Portugal. It is one of the most remarkable examples of 18th-century Portuguese engineering.

Source: Wikipedia

Once a thriving port on the Tagus River, the Alcântara neighborhood has become a busy nightlife hub. Trendy crowds converge on the waterfront eateries and clubs in the converted warehouses of Santo Amaro Docks, near the 25 de Abril Bridge.

Source: Google

Alfama is one of the oldest districts of Lisbon, and is a delightful maze of narrow cobbled streets and ancient houses, which lead up the steep hill from the Tejo Estuary to the castle.

Source: Lisbon Portugal Guide

Henrique Sá Pessoa cuisine is defined as a tasteful cuisine.
The basis of his culinary philosophy is in his influences and references: travels around the world, the passion for Asia, the knowledge of traditional Portuguese cuisine, the life in Lisbon.

Source: Alma

Altice Arena is a multi-purpose indoor arena in Lisbon, Portugal. The arena is among the largest indoor arenas in the European Union and the largest in Portugal.

Source: Wikipedia

places.place_address: Av. Eng. Duarte Pacheco Amoreiras Shopping Center, 1070-103 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Located in an emblematic building, on one of the highest spots of the city, the Amoreiras 360° Panoramic View is a magical location in the city of Lisbon.

Source: Amoreiras 360º Panoramic View

places.place_address: Av. Eng. Duarte Pacheco 2037, 1070-103 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
More than two decades after its opening , Amoreiras Shopping Center won, definitely, a place as a Lisbon’s icon. Placed in the center of the Portuguese capital, with a very bold architecture for its time, it early became a meeting point for the upper middle and upper classes, always demanding quality and attentive to the last fashion trends.

Source: Amoreiras

places.place_address: R. de São Bento, 1249-068 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
The history of the Sao Bento Palace, which is now home to the Assembly of the Republic, goes back to the late 16th century, when a monastery used to fill the site of the present edifice.

Source: Lisbon Tourism

The Rua Augusta Arch is a stone, triumphal arch-like, historical building and visitor attraction in Lisbon, Portugal, on the Praça do Comércio. It was built to commemorate the city's reconstruction after the 1755 earthquake.

Source: Wikipedia

In some of Lisbon’s oldest and most traditional neighbourhoods, you’ll find a nightlife and festive spirit that you’ll find hard to believe in the centre of the city.

Source: Visit Lisboa

places.place_address: R. Nova da Trindade 18, 1200-466 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
The latest chapter in the Chiado culinary empire of José Avillez is a multi-space gastronomic takeover of a former private home. Bairro de Avillez includes a small gourmet shop, a traditional taberna, a charcuterie and cheese counter, and a seafood-driven courtyard restaurant.

Source: Travel + Leisure

places.place_address: Largo de São Carlos 10, 1200-410 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
José Avillez' two-Michelin-starred cathedral of cookery wows diners with painstaking creativity, polished service and first-rate sommelier. Standouts among Lisbon's culinary adventure of a lifetime include suckling pig with orange purée, sea bass with seaweed and bivalves and a stunning roasted butternut squash with miso; paired wines sometimes date to the '70s! Reservations essential.

Source: Lonely Planet

Standing on the waterfront at Belem near the mouth of the River Tagus is the Torre de Belém, arguably the most iconic symbol of Lisbon. Originally conceived as a lighthouse, the tower was eventually built as a defensive fortress.

Source: Planet Ware

The Berardo Collection is internationally acclaimed as a significant art collection that, in addition to its valuable core of works of excellence, also allows us to accompany the main artistic movements of the 20th century.

Source: Visit Lisboa

places.place_address: R. da Bica de Duarte Belo 9, 1200-054 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Lisbon's most photographed street is probably Rua da Bica de Duarte Belo. It's in the historic and picturesque neighborhood of Bica, one of the city's most traditional neighborhoods, known for its small bars and especially for the iconic funicular that runs through it.

Source: Lisbon Lux

places.place_address: Av. Infante Dom Henrique Armazém B, Cais da Pedra, Santa Apolónia, 1900-436 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Part-owned by John Malkovich, this uberhip dockside venue is all glass walls, artful lighting and airy river views. Upstairs, scenesters nibble on sashimi in the minimalist sushi bar, while downstairs the design-conscious restaurant serves highlights such as roasted meats, mushroom risotto and oven-baked fish. There's also an open-air patio cafe facing the river with several other restaurant-cafes next door.

Source: Lonely Planet

The Bosnian mastermind Ljubomir Stanisic oversees this creatively charged Chiado bistro. Start with the namesake 100 Maneiras Strong cocktail in the beautiful downstairs bar, then head upstairs for beautifully prepared dishes showcasing high-end Portuguese ingredients. Classics such as truffled mushroom risotto with wild shrimp are astounding; and options for braver souls include lamb brains.

Source: Lonely Planet

Cais das colunas is located at Praça do Comércio, in the historical center of Lisbon; its marble steps were the noble entrance of the city, where heads of state and other prominent figures have landed.

Source: Lisbonne Idee

Once a seedy area of Lisbon, the riverside Cais do Sodré district has been reborn as one of the city's coolest, a hub of great clubs, bars, restaurants and original shops.

Source: The Guardian

A relaxed and pleasant neighborhood, that many say is almost a city within the city. Comercial and culturally diverse, it offers both traditional and modern experiences of Lisbon as a cosmopolitan city.

Source: On the Grid

This red-brick, neo-Moorish building built in 1892 hosts big concerts and other events, including bullfighting, and houses a museum. Below the stadium is a shopping centre, cinema and food court. It's a popular destination all year long.

Source: Lonely Planet

The ruins of this Gothic church are evocative reminders of the devastation left by the 1755 earthquake. At the time of the earthquake it was the largest church in Lisbon, but today the roofless nave open to the sky is all that remains of the arches and rubble that caved in on the congregation as they were attending mass. 

Source: Go Lisbon

places.place_address: R. das Portas de Santo Antão 58, 1150 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Housed in the Palacio Alverca, a beautiful 17th-century palace built to a Moorish design, the Casa do Alentejo is part of a centre dedicated to Alentejan culture. The first floor restaurant is set in a stunning neo-Renaissance hall awash with gilded wood and fabulous azulejo (tile) panels depicting rural scenes and pastoral landscapes.

Source: USA Today

places.place_address: R. Coelho da Rocha 16, 1250-088 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Immerse yourself in the life and work of Portuguese Modernist founder and author Fernando Pessoa as you wander through his old apartment, browse through his book collection (digitalized), and attempt to decipher some of his handwritten notes.

Source: Lonely Planet

The Tejo Power Station is a unique example of Portugal’s historical, industrial and architectural heritage from the first half of the 20th century. The building was listed as a Building of Public Interest, and today it has been fully restored, including the original machinery.

Source: MAAT

Discover one of the most futuristic and remarkable buildings in Lisbon, facing right onto the Tagus. Also known as the Centre of Research into the Unknown, the building is as innovative and important as the biomedical research performed inside. 

Source: Visit Lisbon

One of the most emblematic neighborhoods of Lisbon, Chiado is always in vogue. Great for people watching, this is a gathering point for everyone, whether for a coffee or an afternoon of shopping.

Source: Home Hunting

With its grand 18th-century arcades, lemon-meringue facades and mosaic cobbles, the riverfront Praça do Comércio is a square to out-pomp them all. Everyone arriving by boat used to disembark here, and it still feels like the gateway to Lisbon, thronging with activity and rattling trams.

Source: Lonely Planet

The beautiful Basilica da Estrela was constructed as a religious obligation by Queen Mary I of Portugal after she gave birth to healthy heir to the Portuguese throne.

Source: Lisbon Portugal Guide

Tucked away in a pocket of Parque Eduardo VII, this trio of glasshouses nurtures tree ferns and camellias in the estufa fría (cool greenhouse), coffee and mango trees in the estufa quente (hot greenhouse) and cacti in the estufa doce (sweet greenhouse).

Source: Lonely Planet

Rock ’n’ roll-themed chain with a high-energy vibe serving burgers & American classics.

Source: Google

places.place_address: Praça do Império 1400-206 Lisboa, 1400-206 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
The Mosteiro dos Jeronimos is a highly ornate monastery that is situated in the Belem district. This grand religious building was historically associated with the early sailors and explorers, as it was from here that Vasco da Gama spent his last night before his voyage to the Far East.

Source: Lisbon Portugal Guide

The concept is ambitious and challenging – as the so-called lifestyle concepts tend to be – with luxury as the over-arching theme. Opened in the historic Tivoli movie theatre on Avenida da Liberdade, the three-level Jncquoi includes a restaurant, a deli and bar, and a men’s fashion store.

Source: The Cool Hunter

Constructed in 1879, Avenida da Liberdade is modeled after boulevards in Paris.  It is 90 meters wide with ten lanes of traffic, divided by pedestrian walkways decorated with gardens. The boulevard is home to fashionable mansions, hotels, theatres, café and designer boutiques.

Source: Portugal Confidential

One of Lisbon’s icons is the fortress-like Sé de Lisboa, built in 1150 on the site of a mosque soon after Christians recaptured the city from the Moors.

Source: Lonely Planet

places.place_address: Av. Infante D. Henrique, Armazém A, Cais da Pedra a Sta Apolónia, 1950-376 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Lux Frágil is Portugal's most internationally renowned venue and one of Lisbon's biggest nightclubs. The venue, which is divided into a club space, bar and terrace, is known for its stunning waterside location and regular appearances from world famous DJs and performers.

Source: Resident Advisor

places.place_address: R. Rodrigues de Faria 103, 1300 - 501 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
What do you get when you introduce an old strip of factory buildings to restaurants, cafés, and creative minds? You get one of the coolest hangout spots in the city.

Source: The Culture Trip

MAAT – Museum of Art, Architecture and Technology is the new cultural centre for Lisbon. It’s a museum where these three areas intertwine within a space of debate, discovery, critical thinking and international dialogue.

Source: Visit Lisboa

It is said the origins of this church dates back to the foundation of Portugal. According to tradition, the first King of Portugal, Dom Afonso Henriques, built in that same location a little chapel to homage the crusaders killed 1147 in the capture of Lisbon.

Source: Lisbon Shopping

Museum in a striking former bank, with design & fashion from the 19th century to the present.

Source: Google

places.place_address: R. Nova do Carvalho 24, 1200-014 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
It’s one of the most popular, most acclaimed and most festive nightspots in Lisbon. It’s a nightclub, music stage, lounge and bar all in one space. It’s rock and roll. It’s cocktail cool. It’s party rockin’.

Source: Portugal Confidential

Lisbon's National Coach Museum features one of the most prominent horse-drawn carriage collections in the world.

Source: Lisbon.net

places.place_address: Esplanada Dom Carlos I s/nº, 1990-005 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
The Oceanário de Lisboa is not just an aquarium, but considering its size, a world in and of itself. The Oceanarium, as it's also often referred to, is Portugal's largest indoor aquarium, holding more than one million gallons of seawater supporting the lives of 8,000 sea creatures.

Source: U.S. News

The beautifully designed Museu do Oriente highlights Portugal’s ties with Asia, from colonial baby steps in Macau to ancestor worship. Strikingly displayed in pitch-black rooms, the permanent collection focuses on the Portuguese presence in Asia and Asian gods.

Source: Lonely Planet

places.place_address: Av. Dom João II, 1900-233 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Designed by acclaimed Spanish architect Santiago Calatrava, the space-age Gare do Oriente is an extraordinary vaulted structure, with slender columns fanning out into a concertina roof to create a kind of geometric, crystalline forest.

Source: Lonely Planet

Park is actually a rooftop parking lot turned into a hip, elevated garden terrace. 180º views of Lisbon can be enjoyed in the sunny afternoon or by starlight through the evening. Potted plants and wooden patio furniture provide a natural ambiance and casual comfort.

Source: Portugal Confidential

places.place_address: R. Dom Pedro V 89, 1250-093 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
We opened the door and entered a whole new world! Thousands of pieces from the 18th to the 20th century, proudly exhibited in five wonderful rooms. A bar or a museum? This was the question that came up when we entered The Chinese Pavilion. Art, airplanes, miniature dolls, medals, military artifacts, unique Bordallo Pinheiro pieces.

Source: Lisboa Cool

Once a seedy brothel in Lisbon's red light district, Pensão Amor (the Guesthouse of Love) is now one of the coolest joints in town.

Source: Julie Dawn Fox

places.place_address: Largo Portas do Sol, 1100-411 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
This original Moorish gateway affords stunning angles over Alfama’s jumble of red rooftops and pastel-coloured houses, underscored by the true blue Tejo.

Source: Lonely Planet

places.place_address: Praça São João Bosco 568, 1350-295 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Most visitors come to this cemetery, the largest in Lisbon, for the view of the River Tejo right next to the artists' plot. But the elaborate baroque family tombstones of the Portuguese aristocracy are also appealing.

Source: Lonely Planet

places.place_address: Praça Dom Pedro IV, 1100-200 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Praça do Rossio is the liveliest area in the capital of Portugal and where many locals and tourists meet up. The square and its surrounding streets are packed with some of the city’s most famous restaurants, bars and shops.

Source: Lisbon.net

The Rossio Railway Station is not just one of the most eye-catching architectural landmarks of Lisbon, but also one of the most intriguing train stations in Europe.

Source: Lisbon Tourism

The Elevador de Santa Justa is a 19th century lift. The structure is adorned with glorious neo-gothic arches and geometric patterns, while inside two sumptuous polished wood carriages whisk passengers up in style.

Source: Lisbon Portugal Guide

places.place_address: Largo de Santo António da Sé, 1100-401 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
The Santo António Church is a Roman Catholic church located in Lisbon, Portugal. It is dedicated to Saint Anthony of Lisbon. According to tradition, the church was built on the site where the saint was born, in 1195.

Source: Wikipedia

places.place_address: R. de Santa Cruz do Castelo, 1100-129 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
São Jorge Castle is a Moorish castle occupying a commanding hilltop overlooking the historic centre of the Portuguese city of Lisbon and Tagus River. The strongly fortified citadel dates from medieval period of Portuguese history, and is one of the main tourist sites of Lisbon.

Source: Wikipedia

The bland facade of the Igreja de Sao Roque hides one of the most exquisite and decorative churches of Lisbon, and possibly Portugal. If a tourist was to only visit the interior of one church in Lisbon the Igreja de Sao Roque would be the church of choice.

Source: Lisbon Portugal Guide

places.place_address: R. da Misericórdia 14, Edifício Espaço Chiado - 1200-273 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
This cocktail bar, club and restaurant located on one of the highest buildings in Lisbon’s historical Chiado district offers breathtaking 270º panoramic views of the city within a sophisticated, modern and luxurious ambience.

Source: 10 Things

places.place: Sophia de Mello Breyner Andresen Lookout
places.description:
A much-loved summertime hangout, this miradouro (lookout) sidles up to the baroque Igreja da Graça. It has an incredible view of the castle sitting plump on the hillside, the river and the Ponte 25 de Abril. Sunset is prime-time viewing at the kiosk terrace.

Source: Lonely Planet

Whether taking fine dining and making it casual or searching for street food that should have a Michelin star, Time Out Market’s mission is to get the best of each city and bring it together under one roof and has become the number one tourist attraction in town.

Source: Time Out

places.place_address: PTE Vasco da Gama, Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
The Ponte Vasco da Gama Lisbon is a massive 17km long bridge that spans the shallow but wide Tagus Estuary to the east of Lisbon. This massive bridge was once Europe longest bridge and was named after Portugal’s great explorer Vasco da Gama.

Source: Lisbon Portugal Guide

places.place_address: Av. Dom João II 40, 1990-094 Lisboa, Portugal
places.description:
Glass-roofed mall sheltering high-street stores, cinema and a food court – upper-level restaurants have outdoor seating with a view.

Source: Lonely Planet

Composed of 14 maritime containers and 2 disabled buses, Village Underground Lisbon is a co-work space for creative activities, as well as a venue for cultural events.

Source: Lisboa Cool

place.place_address: R. Academia das Ciências 19, 1249 Lisboa, Portugal
place.description:
The Academy of Sciences of Lisbon was created in 1779 as an institution to promote the advancement of science and learning for the progress and prosperity of the country.

Source: European Comission

stories.name: What to see in Jeronimos Monastery

storycards.text_content: The Portuguese capital’s food scene is one of the most exciting in Europe right now, offering a mix of innovative and traditional cuisine at restaurants overseen by acclaimed chefs.

storycards.place_address: R. Dom Pedro V 129, 1250-096 Lisboa, Portugal
R. Academia das Ciências 19, 1249 Lisboa, Portugal
storycards.text_content:
It wasn't Lisbon's first Kiko Martins-led restaurant (that would be O Talho) but it was the one that put him in the map. It became one of the city's most popular locations. Cevicheria was born to pay tribute to Peru's national dish, by serving it with salmon, tuna and even codfish, but the best version, the one worth waiting in line for, is the pure ceviche: seasonal white fish, puréed sweet-potato, onions, seaweed and tiger's milk.

Tips:
– Wait for a table with a glass (or two, or three) of pisco sour in your hand.
– To finish your meal, go for a surf & turf mini-sandwich with pork belly and shrimp.
– If you want people on social networks to know where you are, take a picture of the giant octopus on the ceiling.

storycards.place_address: Av. Eng. Duarte Pacheco Amoreiras Shopping Center, 1070-103 Lisboa, Portugal
Largo de São Carlos 10, 1200-410 Lisboa, Portugal

storycards.text_content:
If I say that I saw the future of Portuguese cooking in a martini glass, you might conclude that I was having drunken visions.

Not at the meal and moment in question: when a server at the chef José Avillez’s brilliant restaurant Belcanto, in Lisbon, set the second in a series of amuse bouches before me. It was called an “inverted martini,” because the olive had the starring role, in the form of a pool of green juice. Gin played the cameo, having been turned into a translucent sphere the size and shape of an olive.

It was pretty, witty and plenty delicious. And it spoke to the cunning and creativity of Mr. Avillez, a rising young star on the Portuguese food scene and a big reason Lisbon is such a culinary joy, especially these days.

Over the last year Mr. Avillez, 32, has essentially opened two new restaurants. Essentially because Belcanto, in the city’s Chiado neighborhood, had been around for many decades before he took it over and gave it an elegant face-lift and entirely new, slightly avant-garde menu about six months ago. My long lunch there was perhaps the best meal I’ve eaten in 2012 so far.

Mr. Avillez’s other, much more casual new restaurant, Cantinho do Avillez, is just blocks away, only a few months older and a convivial delight. It features a succinct menu of hearty Portuguese bistro fare that departs from the Lisbon norm by paying a bit more attention to fowl, organ meats and African and Asian spices, which underscore ethnic bridges built in Portugal’s colonial past.

storycards.place_address: Av. Infante Dom Henrique Armazém B, Cais da Pedra, Santa Apolónia, 1900-436 Lisboa, Portugal

storycards.text_content:
Set on the dock at Santa Apolónia, this fashionable and trendy venue has a well-known Hollywood name behind - American actor John Malkovich, who even pops in unannounced on occasion.

The menu here is international, but also celebrated Portuguese culinary tradition with dishes like braised turbot with spinach and clams garnished with coriander.

Needless to say, the wine list complements the excellent choice of gastronomy. Upstairs, a minimalist sushi bar serves excellent sashimi, tempura, kushiyaki and other Japanese delights.

For a less formal experience, the riverside bar offers a lighter menu (and wonderful views) and is especially popular at lunchtime.

storycards.place_address: R. Nova da Trindade 18, 1200-466 Lisboa, Portugal

storycards.text_content:
There he goes! He’s doing again! Opening yet another restaurant that is sure to be an instant Lisbon classic.

Popular and respected Portuguese chef José Avillez opens a new restaurant in Chiado, near foodie favorites Belcanto, Minibar, Café Avillez, Pizzaria Avillez and Cantinho do Avillez. The casual venue is aptly named Bairro (“neighborhood”) do Avillez, featuring a variety of areas akin to your local neighborhood.

”Bairro do Avillez has different gastronomic offerings, inspired by the best Portuguese flavors, presented in the following areas: Taberna (tavern), Páteo (patio) and Mercearia (grocery store)”, explains Avillez. I imagine a quarter inspired by Lisbon neighborhoods and from my own memories.”

storycards.place_address: R. da Misericórdia 14, Edifício Espaço Chiado - 1200-273 Lisboa, Portugal

storycards.text_content:
Visit one of the most exclusive clubs in Lisbon.

The Silk Club, on the top floor of a building in Rua da Misericórdia, is a member of the World’s Finest Clubs and offers a very exclusive ambiance. To add a touch of total sophistication to your stay in the city, this is the ideal destination. Dress in style and climb up to this bar with its fabulous and stunning view of the whole city.

Wherever you look, you’ll see something new and worthy of comment. With its minimalist decor, to better emphasise the unique view, you can try various original cocktails, as well as genuine Japanese cuisine.

With a DJ and sushi chefs, this is a unique experience in Lisbon. Visit the Silk Club and discover a more cosmopolitan and reserved side of Lisbon.

‼️Slowly lift one leg up by contracting the glutes
•
•
👍🏼Make sure to keep the hips relatively in line, trying not to rotate through the trunk as you alternate leg lifts
•
•
✅You can hold this plank for 20-30 seconds or try and perform 5-10 reps on each leg.
•
•
•
💪🏽This is an awesome exercise to add to your core work or as a warm up exercise for your lower body workouts🏋🏼

Throwback to when the moon got us all with are heads up staring at the sky in all its beauty.
🌒

Watching the moon turning blood red and then white again had me thinking how change and darkness are so vital in life just as much as stall and light. It's a constant cycle that nature keeps reminding us of every day with the colour of the leaves turning orange, the rainbow that comes after the storm and the sun that raises and dies every single day. 
Change is natural and it's okay to gently outgrow from something that it's not longer good for us.
🌀
Here's to all of us who were brave enough to start brand new today, to those who did it already, and those who aren't ready yet, but will find the strength soon enough.
